        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose high angular resolution Band 7 observations of the continuum (356 GHz) and CO(J=3-2) line emission from a sample of Taurus binaries.  High angular resolution is required 
for the science goal, which is to accurately measure protoplanetary disk radii in very close stellar binaries and compare them with predictions of models.  The continuum emission is the 
principal target for this proposal, though we do reserve a spectral window for relatively low velocity resolution observations of the CO(J=3-2) line, to try to detect any line emission from 
these disks.  Such line emission, if detected, will allow constraints on both the disk inclination and the host star mass.  Obtaining these quantities separately from the use of astrometry 
or the continuum observations will be very useful in allowing us to test truncation models. 
A velocity resolution of 0.1 km/s will be sufficient for kinematic host star/binary mass estimates in all but the most face-on systems.

The use of zero velocity offset for observation of the CO line will be fine, as the systemic velocity of all systems in the sample is much less than half the aggregate bandwidth of the 
spectral window the CO line is placed in (~20 vs. ~ 200 km/s).</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
