    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Stellar binaries are ubiquitous. Furthermore, binaries regularly bear circumstellar/system disks. Planets form out of disk material dynamically stable in the presence of the stars. The regions of stability are determined by star-disk interactions that dynamically carve cavities into circumbinary disks and truncate circumstellar disks. Thus, determining these radii is essential to deciphering the role multiplicity plays in the shaping planet formation. The degree of truncation is determined by the binary orbital parameters, so studies of these interactions require knowledge of the stellar orbits. This has proven challenging, as the systems with well-determined orbits are typically those for which dynamical interactions have stripped away much of the circumstellar material. However, we have assembled a carefully chosen list of targets that both have constrained orbits and evidence of enough circumstellar material to image well at high resolution with ALMA. We propose high-angular resolution (0.1 arcsecond) Band 7 observations of the disks in these pre-main sequence binaries to resolve individual disk radii and determine if they are in accord with models of star-disk interactions.</prp:abstract>
